  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-3-docs/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs-new/TUTORIAL.md', content='# Tutorial: from zero to your first custom tool\n\nThis tutorial is written against the pinned checkout in this working tree. Every symbol referenced below exists in this snapshot. The goal is not to describe an imaginary plugin API; it is to show how D.U.H. is actually assembled today, then use that knowledge to build and exercise a custom tool end to end.\n\nThe important constraint to keep in mind is architectural: the runtime is built around a small kernel (`duh/kernel/`), a set of ports (`duh/ports/`), and concrete adapters/tools layered around them. A “custom tool” in this codebase is simply a Python object that satisfies the `duh.kernel.tool.Tool` protocol well enough for `duh.adapters.native_executor.NativeExecutor` and `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools()`-style consumers to use it.\n\nWe will go through four stages:\n\n1. Install the project in editable mode.\n2. Run the CLI in deterministic stub mode so you can see the real request path without external credentials.\n3. Explore the tool runtime with a tiny in-memory example.\n4. Build a real custom tool class, register it with the native executor, add an approval gate, and make the first call.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Install the checkout\n\nFrom the repository root, install the package in editable mode.\n\n```bash\npython3 -m pip install -e .\n```\n\nExpected output will vary by environment, but it should end with a successful install similar to:\n\n```text\nSuccessfully installed duh-cli-0.8.0\n```\n\nIf you want to confirm that the CLI entry point resolves, run:\n\n```bash\nduh --version\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nduh 0.8.0\n```\n\nThat version string comes from the installed package metadata and the parser built in `duh/cli/parser.py`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Run D.U.H. without credentials using the built-in stub provider\n\nThis repository includes a deterministic offline provider in `duh.adapters.stub_provider.StubProvider`. It is activated by environment variable, not by a separate command-line flag.\n\nThe relevant pieces are:\n\n- `duh.adapters.stub_provider.stub_provider_enabled()`\n- `duh.providers.registry.resolve_provider_name(...)`\n- `duh.providers.registry.build_model_backend(...)`\n\nWhen `DUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1` is set, provider resolution short-circuits to `"stub"`, and the backend returns a callable that yields a canned event stream.\n\nRun this:\n\n```bash\nDUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1 duh -p "hello"\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nstub-ok\n```\n\nThat exact text is the default value returned by `duh.adapters.stub_provider.stub_response_text()`.\n\nYou can override the canned response too:\n\n```bash\nDUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1 DUH_STUB_RESPONSE="hello from stub" duh -p "hello"\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nhello from stub\n```\n\nThis is useful because it exercises the real print-mode stack:\n\n- `duh.cli.main.main()` parses arguments.\n- `duh.cli.runner.run_print_mode()` builds a session.\n- `duh.cli.session_builder.SessionBuilder.build()` resolves provider, tools, executor, approver, store, and engine.\n- `duh.kernel.engine.Engine.run()` appends the user message and streams events.\n- `duh.kernel.loop.query()` calls the provider and yields events.\n- The runner renders `text_delta` events to stdout.\n\nSo even in stub mode, you are traversing the actual architecture.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Inspect the tool runtime with real classes\n\nBefore writing a custom tool, it helps to see what the built-in runtime expects.\n\nA tool call in this codebase revolves around three kernel dataclasses/protocols from `duh.kernel.tool`:\n\n- `ToolContext`\n- `ToolResult`\n- `Tool`\n\nThe executor most callers use is `duh.adapters.native_executor.NativeExecutor`, which exposes:\n\n- `register(self, tool: Any) -> None`\n- `get_tool(self, name: str) -> Any | None`\n- `tool_names`\n- `run(self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any], *, tool_use_id: str = "", context: Any = None) -> str | dict[str, Any]`\n\nHere is a minimal runnable script that creates the built-in `TaskTool`, registers it, and calls it through the executor.\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\nfrom duh.tools.task_tool import TaskTool\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    executor = NativeExecutor(tools=[TaskTool()], cwd=".")\n\n    created = await executor.run(\n        "Task",\n        {"action": "create", "description": "Write tutorial notes"},\n    )\n    print(created)\n\n    listed = await executor.run("Task", {"action": "list"})\n    print(listed)\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRun it with:\n\n```bash\npython3 /tmp/duh-task-demo.py\n```\n\nExpected output will look like this:\n\n```text\nCreated task <id>: Write tutorial notes\nTasks (0/1 completed):\n  [ ] <id> — Write tutorial notes\n```\n\nThe exact task id is random because `duh.kernel.tasks.TaskManager.create()` uses `uuid.uuid4().hex[:8]`.\n\nWhat this teaches you:\n\n1. A tool is just an object with a `name`, `description`, `input_schema`, and async `call(...)` method.\n2. `NativeExecutor.run(...)` looks up the tool by `name`.\n3. If the tool returns `ToolResult(is_error=True)`, the executor raises `RuntimeError(result.output)`.\n4. If it returns a successful `ToolResult`, the executor hands the string output back to the caller.\n\nThat is the exact mechanism we will use for the custom tool.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Understand the approval seam before adding your own tool\n\nD.U.H. keeps approval separate from tool implementation.\n\nThere are two approval layers in this checkout:\n\n1. Tool-local checks via `tool.check_permissions(input, context)`.\n2. Session-level approval via `Deps.approve`, which is called by the query loop before execution.\n\nThe protocol for the second layer lives in `duh.ports.approver.ApprovalGate`:\n\n```python\nclass ApprovalGate(Protocol):\n    async def check(\n        self,\n        tool_name: str,\n        input: dict[str, Any],\n    ) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        ...\n```\n\nThe query loop expects dictionaries like:\n\n- `{"allowed": True}`\n- `{"allowed": False, "reason": "..."}`\n\nThat means you do **not** need to bake all policy into the tool class. You can keep the tool focused on its job, and enforce environment-specific approval with an `ApprovalGate` implementation or a plain async callable assigned to `Deps.approve`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Build a simple custom tool class\n\nCreate a file anywhere convenient for experimentation. The class below uses only real symbols from this checkout.\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult\n\n\nclass HelloTool:\n    name = "Hello"\n    description = "Return a greeting for the requested name."\n    input_schema: dict[str, Any] = {\n        "type": "object",\n        "properties": {\n            "name": {\n                "type": "string",\n                "description": "Name to greet.",\n            },\n        },\n        "required": ["name"],\n    }\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:\n        return True\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool:\n        return False\n\n    async def call(self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:\n        name = input.get("name", "")\n        if not name:\n            return ToolResult(output="name is required", is_error=True)\n        return ToolResult(output=f"Hello, {name}!")\n\n    async def check_permissions(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        return {"allowed": True}\n```\n\nThis shape is intentionally familiar if you looked at built-in tools such as:\n\n- `duh.tools.read.ReadTool`\n- `duh.tools.write.WriteTool`\n- `duh.tools.task_tool.TaskTool`\n\nNow wire it into a real executor.\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\n\nfrom hello_tool import HelloTool\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    executor = NativeExecutor(tools=[HelloTool()], cwd=".")\n    result = await executor.run("Hello", {"name": "D.U.H."})\n    print(result)\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nHello, D.U.H.!\n```\n\nAt this point you have a fully working custom tool in the same runtime used by the CLI.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Validate your tool schema the same way the registry does\n\nThe built-in registry validates each eager-loaded tool with `duh.kernel.schema_validator.validate_tool_schema(...)`.\n\nYou should do the same while developing a custom tool.\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.schema_validator import validate_tool_schema\n\nfrom hello_tool import HelloTool\n\nwarnings = validate_tool_schema(HelloTool.name, HelloTool.input_schema)\nprint(warnings)\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\n[]\n```\n\nIf you break the schema, for example by omitting the root `"type": "object"`, `validate_tool_schema(...)` raises `SchemaValidationError`.\n\nThat is worth doing early because model providers expect proper JSON schema for tool declarations.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Add an approval policy for your tool\n\nNow let’s add a session-level approval gate using the real `Deps` shape from `duh.kernel.deps`.\n\nHere is a tiny approval gate that denies one specific input and allows everything else.\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom typing import Any\n\n\nclass DemoApprovalGate:\n    async def check(self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        if tool_name == "Hello" and input.get("name") == "blocked":\n            return {"allowed": False, "reason": "blocked by DemoApprovalGate"}\n        return {"allowed": True}\n```\n\nAnd here is a script that exercises both the gate and the tool by calling the query loop directly.\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\nfrom duh.kernel.loop import query\nfrom duh.kernel.messages import Message\nfrom duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult\n\n\nclass HelloTool:\n    name = "Hello"\n    description = "Return a greeting for the requested name."\n    input_schema = {\n        "type": "object",\n        "properties": {\n            "name": {\n                "type": "string",\n                "description": "Name to greet.",\n            }\n        },\n        "required": ["name"],\n    }\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:\n        return True\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool:\n        return False\n\n    async def call(self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:\n        return ToolResult(output=f"Hello, {input[\'name\']}!")\n\n    async def check_permissions(self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n\nclass DemoApprovalGate:\n    async def check(self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        if tool_name == "Hello" and input.get("name") == "blocked":\n            return {"allowed": False, "reason": "blocked by DemoApprovalGate"}\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n\nclass DemoProvider:\n    async def stream(\n        self,\n        *,\n        messages,\n        system_prompt="",\n        model="",\n        tools=None,\n        thinking=None,\n        max_tokens=None,\n        **kwargs,\n    ):\n        text = messages[-1].text\n        if text == "allow":\n            assistant = Message(\n                role="assistant",\n                content=[\n                    {\n                        "type": "tool_use",\n                        "id": "toolu_1",\n                        "name": "Hello",\n                        "input": {"name": "D.U.H."},\n                    }\n                ],\n                metadata={"stop_reason": "tool_use"},\n            )\n        else:\n            assistant = Message(\n                role="assistant",\n                content=[\n                    {\n                        "type": "tool_use",\n                        "id": "toolu_2",\n                        "name": "Hello",\n                        "input": {"name": "blocked"},\n                    }\n                ],\n                metadata={"stop_reason": "tool_use"},\n            )\n        yield {"type": "assistant", "message": assistant}\n\n\nasync def run_case(prompt: str) -> None:\n    tool = HelloTool()\n\n    async def run_tool(tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any]) -> str:\n        if tool_name != tool.name:\n            raise KeyError(tool_name)\n        result = await tool.call(input, ToolContext(cwd="."))\n        if result.is_error:\n            raise RuntimeError(result.output)\n        return str(result.output)\n\n    deps = Deps(\n        call_model=DemoProvider().stream,\n        run_tool=run_tool,\n        approve=DemoApprovalGate().check,\n    )\n\n    async for event in query(\n        messages=[Message(role="user", content=prompt)],\n        deps=deps,\n        tools=[tool],\n        model="stub-model",\n        max_turns=1,\n    ):\n        if event["type"] in {"tool_use", "tool_result", "done"}:\n            print(event)\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    print("-- allowed --")\n    await run_case("allow")\n    print("-- denied --")\n    await run_case("deny")\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\n-- allowed --\n{\'type\': \'tool_use\', \'id\': \'toolu_1\', \'name\': \'Hello\', \'input\': {\'name\': \'D.U.H.\'}}\n{\'type\': \'tool_result\', \'tool_use_id\': \'toolu_1\', \'output\': \'Hello, D.U.H.!\', \'is_error\': False}\n{\'type\': \'done\', \'stop_reason\': \'max_turns\', \'turns\': 1}\n-- denied --\n{\'type\': \'tool_use\', \'id\': \'toolu_2\', \'name\': \'Hello\', \'input\': {\'name\': \'blocked\'}}\n{\'type\': \'tool_result\', \'tool_use_id\': \'toolu_2\', \'output\': \'Tool use denied: blocked by DemoApprovalGate\', \'is_error\': True}\n{\'type\': \'done\', \'stop_reason\': \'max_turns\', \'turns\': 1}\n```\n\nA few details are worth noting:\n\n- The approval decision is made in `duh.kernel.loop.query()` before `deps.run_tool(...)` is called.\n- The denial is turned into a synthetic `tool_result` event with `is_error=True`.\n- Because `max_turns=1`, the loop exits after the first tool round and reports `stop_reason: \'max_turns\'`.\n\nThis is the real approval-policy seam the CLI uses too, just with simpler wiring.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Register a custom tool beside the built-ins\n\nIf you want the built-in tools and your tool together, you do not need to reimplement the registry. Use `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools()` and append your tool.\n\n```python\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\nfrom duh.tools.registry import get_all_tools\n\nfrom hello_tool import HelloTool\n\ntools = get_all_tools()\ntools.append(HelloTool())\nexecutor = NativeExecutor(tools=tools, cwd=".")\n\nprint("Hello" in executor.tool_names)\nprint("Read" in executor.tool_names)\nprint("Task" in executor.tool_names)\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nTrue\nTrue\nTrue\n```\n\nThis is the closest thing in the current codebase to “registration”: the registry simply returns a list of tool instances, and the executor indexes them by name.\n\nThere is no dedicated plugin manifest for native Python tools in this snapshot. For documentation accuracy, that matters: adding a new built-in tool today means updating code that constructs the tool list, most directly `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools()`.\n\n---\n\n## 9. See how the CLI builds the same pieces\n\nOnce you understand the low-level pieces, the CLI session builder becomes easy to read.\n\n`duh.cli.session_builder.SessionBuilder.build()` does the following in order:\n\n1. Resolves a provider with `resolve_provider_name(...)`.\n2. Builds the backend with `build_model_backend(...)`.\n3. Builds a `PathPolicy`.\n4. Loads skills and deferred tools.\n5. Calls `get_all_tools(...)`.\n6. Builds a `NativeExecutor(tools=tools, cwd=self.cwd)`.\n7. Builds an approver.\n8. Builds `Deps(call_model=..., run_tool=executor.run, approve=..., compact=...)`.\n9. Builds `EngineConfig(...)`.\n10. Constructs `Engine(...)`.\n\nHere is a small script that recreates the same pattern with your own custom tool, but without invoking the entire CLI.\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\nfrom duh.adapters.stub_provider import StubProvider\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import Engine, EngineConfig\nfrom duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult\n\n\nclass HelloTool:\n    name = "Hello"\n    description = "Return a greeting for the requested name."\n    input_schema = {\n        "type": "object",\n        "properties": {\n            "name": {\n                "type": "string",\n                "description": "Name to greet.",\n            }\n        },\n        "required": ["name"],\n    }\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:\n        return True\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool:\n        return False\n\n    async def call(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:\n        return ToolResult(output=f"Hello, {input[\'name\']}!")\n\n    async def check_permissions(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> dict[str, object]:\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    hello_tool = HelloTool()\n    executor = NativeExecutor(tools=[hello_tool], cwd=".")\n\n    deps = Deps(\n        call_model=StubProvider(model="stub-model").stream,\n        run_tool=executor.run,\n    )\n\n    config = EngineConfig(\n        model="stub-model",\n        system_prompt="You are a helpful assistant.",\n        tools=[hello_tool],\n        max_turns=1,\n    )\n\n    engine = Engine(deps=deps, config=config)\n\n    async for event in engine.run("hello"):\n        print(event["type"])\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\nsession\ntext_delta\nassistant\ndone\n```\n\nWhy does your `HelloTool` not get called here? Because `StubProvider.stream(...)` in this repository always emits a plain assistant response and never asks for tools. That is exactly why stub mode is useful for CLI smoke tests but not for tool-invocation demos.\n\nTo test actual tool execution, you either:\n\n- call `NativeExecutor.run(...)` directly, or\n- call `duh.kernel.loop.query(...)` with a provider that yields a `tool_use` block, like the `DemoProvider` example above.\n\n---\n\n## 10. First custom tool call, end to end\n\nLet’s put everything together in the smallest realistic end-to-end example: custom tool, approval policy, provider-generated tool request, and query-loop execution.\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\nfrom duh.kernel.loop import query\nfrom duh.kernel.messages import Message\nfrom duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult\n\n\nclass HelloTool:\n    name = "Hello"\n    description = "Return a greeting for the requested name."\n    input_schema = {\n        "type": "object",\n        "properties": {\n            "name": {\n                "type": "string",\n                "description": "Name to greet.",\n            }\n        },\n        "required": ["name"],\n    }\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:\n        return True\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool:\n        return False\n\n    async def call(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:\n        return ToolResult(output=f"Hello, {input[\'name\']}!")\n\n    async def check_permissions(self, input: dict[str, object], context: ToolContext) -> dict[str, object]:\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n\nclass AllowAllApproval:\n    async def check(self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, object]) -> dict[str, object]:\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n\nclass ToolCallingProvider:\n    async def stream(\n        self,\n        *,\n        messages,\n        system_prompt="",\n        model="",\n        tools=None,\n        thinking=None,\n        max_tokens=None,\n        **kwargs,\n    ):\n        yield {\n            "type": "assistant",\n            "message": Message(\n                role="assistant",\n                content=[\n                    {\n                        "type": "tool_use",\n                        "id": "hello-1",\n                        "name": "Hello",\n                        "input": {"name": "world"},\n                    }\n                ],\n                metadata={"stop_reason": "tool_use"},\n            ),\n        }\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    tool = HelloTool()\n\n    async def run_tool(tool_name: str, input: dict[str, object]) -> str:\n        result = await tool.call(input, ToolContext(cwd="."))\n        if result.is_error:\n            raise RuntimeError(result.output)\n        return str(result.output)\n\n    deps = Deps(\n        call_model=ToolCallingProvider().stream,\n        run_tool=run_tool,\n        approve=AllowAllApproval().check,\n    )\n\n    async for event in query(\n        messages=[Message(role="user", content="say hello")],\n        deps=deps,\n        tools=[tool],\n        model="stub-model",\n        max_turns=1,\n    ):\n        print(event)\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```text\n{\'type\': \'assistant\', \'message\': Message(...)}\n{\'type\': \'tool_use\', \'id\': \'hello-1\', \'name\': \'Hello\', \'input\': {\'name\': \'world\'}}\n{\'type\': \'tool_result\', \'tool_use_id\': \'hello-1\', \'output\': \'Hello, world!\', \'is_error\': False}\n{\'type\': \'tool_result_message\', \'message\': Message(...)}\n{\'type\': \'done\', \'stop_reason\': \'max_turns\', \'turns\': 1}\n```\n\nThe `Message(...)` repr includes generated ids and timestamps, so those parts will vary. The event sequence is the important part.\n\nThis is your first custom tool call, using the exact event semantics the engine and runner depend on.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Where to make the same change in the real application\n\nIf you want your custom tool to become part of the actual CLI rather than just a script-local experiment, the current extension point is code-level registration.\n\n### Option A: private/local registration\n\nIf you control the session-building code, append your tool to the tool list after calling `get_all_tools(...)` and before constructing `NativeExecutor`.\n\nThat pattern matches how `SessionBuilder` already composes skills, deferred tools, MCP wrappers, and core tools.\n\n### Option B: built-in native tool\n\nTo make it a true built-in tool in this snapshot, update `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools()` so it imports and appends your tool class in the same style as `TaskTool`, `HTTPTool`, or `TodoWriteTool`.\n\nThat is the real “registration” path today.\n\n### Option C: expose it to the model in a session-local harness\n\nIf you are building an integration test, benchmark, or alternative runner, you can skip the global registry and just pass your tool object in:\n\n- to `NativeExecutor(tools=[...])`\n- to `EngineConfig(tools=[...])`\n- or to `query(..., tools=[...])`\n\nThat is often the fastest path when prototyping.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Common mistakes when adding a tool\n\n### Mistake 1: inventing a plugin API that does not exist\n\nThis checkout does support deferred tools and plugin-discovered metadata for `ToolSearch`, but the core native runtime still works on concrete Python objects in a tool list. If you are adding a new built-in tool, you need a class and a registry entry, not just a manifest.\n\n### Mistake 2: returning plain strings from `call(...)`\n\nBuilt-in tools return `ToolResult`, and `NativeExecutor.run(...)` is designed around that. Keep your tool implementation aligned with the `Tool` protocol.\n\n### Mistake 3: skipping schema validation\n\nThe model only knows how to call tools because their `input_schema` is exposed upstream. Bad schemas cause downstream failures that are much harder to debug than calling `validate_tool_schema(...)` once.\n\n### Mistake 4: coupling approval to rendering\n\nApproval belongs either in `tool.check_permissions(...)` or `Deps.approve`, not in the renderer and not in the provider.\n\n### Mistake 5: trying to test tool invocation with `StubProvider`\n\n`StubProvider` is excellent for smoke testing the CLI and event plumbing, but it does not emit tool-use blocks. Use `NativeExecutor.run(...)` or a tiny provider stub that yields `assistant` messages containing `tool_use` blocks.\n\n---\n\n## 13. What you know now\n\nBy this point you have used the same concrete pieces the real app uses:\n\n- `duh.adapters.stub_provider.StubProvider`\n- `duh.adapters.native_executor.NativeExecutor`\n- `duh.kernel.tool.ToolContext`\n- `duh.kernel.tool.ToolResult`\n- `duh.kernel.deps.Deps`\n- `duh.kernel.loop.query`\n- `duh.kernel.engine.Engine`\n- `duh.kernel.engine.EngineConfig`\n- `duh.kernel.schema_validator.validate_tool_schema`\n- `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools`\n\nThat is enough to move from “I can run D.U.H.” to “I can add and exercise a custom tool using the real architecture.”\n\nThe architecture guide explains how these parts fit into the larger session pipeline, and the API reference gives exact signatures for the kernel and port layer if you want to extend more than just the tool surface.\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-3-docs/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs-new/ARCHITECTURE.md', content='# Architecture\n\nD.U.H. is structured as a small kernel surrounded by adapters, CLI surfaces, and tool implementations. The codebase deliberately separates the **conversation engine**, **provider abstraction**, **tool execution**, **approval policy**, **rendering**, and **state persistence** so that the same runtime can power print mode, REPL mode, TUI mode, SDK-style NDJSON mode, and bridge/server integrations.\n\nThis document is grounded in the current source tree at commit `645d91a`. It focuses on the architecture that actually exists in this snapshot rather than aspirational APIs. Where the code offers extension seams, those seams are named precisely and tied back to concrete files.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Top-level module layout\n\nAt a high level, the repository is organized into layers.\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n    CLI[duh/cli\\nargument parsing, runners, REPL, slash commands]\n    UI[duh/ui\\nTextual TUI components]\n    KERNEL[duh/kernel\\nengine, query loop, messages, safety helpers]\n    PORTS[duh/ports\\nprovider / executor / store / renderer / approver / context / memory protocols]\n    ADAPTERS[duh/adapters\\nproviders, executor, approvers, file store, renderers, compaction]\n    TOOLS[duh/tools\\nconcrete tool implementations + registry]\n    PROVIDERS[duh/providers\\nprovider selection and model registry]\n    SECURITY[duh/security\\npolicy, path boundaries, audit, sandbox, trifecta checks]\n    PLUGINS[duh/plugins\\nplugin discovery for deferred tools]\n    AUTH[duh/auth\\ncredential loading and OAuth persistence]\n\n    CLI --> KERNEL\n    UI --> CLI\n    CLI --> PROVIDERS\n    CLI --> TOOLS\n    CLI --> ADAPTERS\n    KERNEL --> PORTS\n    ADAPTERS --> PORTS\n    TOOLS --> KERNEL\n    TOOLS --> SECURITY\n    CLI --> SECURITY\n    ADAPTERS --> SECURITY\n    PROVIDERS --> ADAPTERS\n    PROVIDERS --> AUTH\n    CLI --> PLUGINS\n```\n\nThe important architectural split is between **ports** and **adapters**.\n\n- `duh/ports/` defines abstract interfaces such as `ModelProvider`, `ToolExecutor`, `ApprovalGate`, `Renderer`, `SessionStore`, `ContextManager`, and `MemoryStore`.\n- `duh/adapters/` provides concrete implementations such as `AnthropicProvider`, `OpenAIProvider`, `OllamaProvider`, `NativeExecutor`, file-backed stores, structured logging, and approvers.\n- `duh/kernel/` owns the domain model and orchestration logic, especially the `Engine`, `query()` loop, messages, context-management helpers, taint tracking, and execution safety rules.\n\nThe CLI layer (`duh/cli/`) is not just a thin parser. It is the composition root that decides which provider backend, tool list, approver, executor, and renderer to assemble for a session.\n\n### Major directories and their roles\n\n#### `duh/cli/`\n\nThis is the entrypoint and user-facing orchestration layer.\n\n- `main.py` dispatches subcommands and mode selection.\n- `parser.py` defines the unified CLI surface.\n- `runner.py` implements print mode.\n- `repl.py` implements the interactive readline-based REPL.\n- `session_builder.py` factors shared session assembly used by print mode and REPL.\n- `slash_commands.py` implements command dispatch for the REPL/TUI slash-command surface.\n- `sdk_runner.py`, `batch.py`, `review.py`, `doctor.py`, and `prewarm.py` provide specialized entry paths.\n\n#### `duh/kernel/`\n\nThis directory is the runtime core.\n\nImportant modules include:\n\n- `engine.py`: conversation/session lifecycle wrapper.\n- `loop.py`: the core model→tool→model query loop.\n- `deps.py`: dependency injection seams.\n- `messages.py`: canonical message and content-block types.\n- `tool.py`: tool protocol, runtime context, and result type.\n- `tokens.py`: token counting, context limits, cost estimation.\n- `untrusted.py`: taint-aware string propagation.\n- `confirmation.py`: HMAC confirmation tokens.\n- `context_gate.py`, `file_size_guard.py`, `query_guard.py`: guard rails against pathological or unsafe input growth.\n- `skill.py`, `templates.py`, `plan_mode.py`, `snapshot.py`: higher-level conversation features.\n\n#### `duh/ports/`\n\nThis is the abstract boundary layer. The kernel knows these shapes, not concrete SDKs.\n\n- `provider.py`: `ModelProvider`\n- `executor.py`: `ToolExecutor`\n- `approver.py`: `ApprovalGate`\n- `renderer.py`: `Renderer`\n- `store.py`: `SessionStore`\n- `context.py`: `ContextManager`\n- `memory.py`: `MemoryStore`, `MemoryHeader`\n\n#### `duh/adapters/`\n\nAdapters translate between port abstractions and concrete systems.\n\nExamples:\n\n- model providers: `anthropic.py`, `openai.py`, `openai_chatgpt.py`, `ollama.py`, `gemini.py`, `groq.py`, `stub_provider.py`\n- executor: `native_executor.py`\n- storage: `file_store.py`, `memory_store.py`\n- approval: `approvers.py`\n- compaction: `simple_compactor.py`, `compact/*`, `model_compactor.py`\n- sandboxing: `sandbox/landlock.py`, `sandbox/seatbelt.py`, `sandbox/network.py`\n- rendering: `renderers.py`\n\n#### `duh/tools/`\n\nConcrete tool classes live here. The registry in `duh/tools/registry.py` instantiates them. These tools are not part of the kernel; the kernel only deals in generic tool-use requests and tool results.\n\nRepresentative examples:\n\n- filesystem: `read.py`, `write.py`, `edit.py`, `multi_edit.py`, `notebook_edit.py`\n- shell/system: `bash.py`, `docker_tool.py`, `db_tool.py`, `http_tool.py`\n- discovery/meta: `glob_tool.py`, `grep.py`, `tool_search.py`, `skill_tool.py`\n- workflow: `task_tool.py`, `todo_tool.py`, `test_impact.py`, `worktree.py`\n- interactive/user: `ask_user_tool.py`\n- multi-agent: `agent_tool.py`, `swarm_tool.py`\n\n#### `duh/providers/`\n\n`registry.py` is the most important file here. It resolves providers from flags or environment, maps model aliases, selects defaults, and returns a callable backend through `build_model_backend(...)`.\n\n#### `duh/security/`\n\nThis layer contains security policy, path controls, audit logging, and the “trifecta” protection against dangerous capability combinations.\n\nKey files include:\n\n- `path_policy.py`\n- `policy.py`\n- `audit.py`\n- `trifecta.py`\n- `network_policy.py`\n\n---\n\n## 2. Request flow: one user prompt from CLI parse to rendered response\n\nThe cleanest way to understand D.U.H. is to trace a print-mode request.\n\n### Step 1: CLI parse and mode selection\n\n`duh.cli.main.main()` is the first significant application entry point.\n\nIts main jobs are:\n\n1. install signal handlers\n2. call `build_parser()` from `duh.cli.parser`\n3. dispatch subcommands (`doctor`, `constitution`, `security`, `audit`, `batch`, `review`, `bridge`)\n4. decide between SDK mode, print mode, TUI mode, and REPL mode\n\nFor a command like:\n\n```text\nduh -p "fix the bug"\n```\n\n`main()` ends up calling `asyncio.run(run_print_mode(args))` from `duh.cli.runner`.\n\n### Step 2: session assembly in `SessionBuilder`\n\n`duh.cli.runner.run_print_mode()` delegates nearly all dependency assembly to `duh.cli.session_builder.SessionBuilder.build()`.\n\nThat builder performs the shared startup sequence for print mode and REPL:\n\n1. **Provider resolution** via `_build_provider()`:\n   - `resolve_provider_name(...)` from `duh.providers.registry`\n   - `build_model_backend(...)` from `duh.providers.registry`\n2. **Path policy creation** via `_build_path_policy()`:\n   - `PathPolicy` based on the git root or current working directory\n3. **Skill and deferred-tool loading**:\n   - `load_all_skills(...)` from `duh.kernel.skill`\n   - plugin discovery through `duh.plugins`\n4. **Tool construction**:\n   - `get_all_tools(...)` from `duh.tools.registry`\n5. **Config, hooks, and MCP setup**:\n   - `load_config(...)`\n   - `HookRegistry`\n   - `MCPExecutor.from_config(...)` when configured\n6. **System prompt assembly**:\n   - base constitution/system prompt\n   - optional coordinator prompt\n   - brief mode instructions\n   - instruction files\n   - memory prompt\n   - environment block\n   - git context block\n   - skills/templates/deferred-tools hint blocks\n7. **Runtime assembly**:\n   - `NativeExecutor`\n   - approver (`AutoApprover`, `InteractiveApprover`, or `TieredApprover`)\n   - `SimpleCompactor`\n   - `FileStore`\n   - `Deps`\n   - `EngineConfig`\n   - `Engine`\n8. **Optional session resume**:\n   - previous messages restored from the session store\n   - optional summarizing compaction on resume\n\nThis builder is the application’s composition root.\n\n### Step 3: engine turn setup\n\n`duh.kernel.engine.Engine.run()` is called with the prompt.\n\nThe engine is responsible for session lifecycle rather than provider details. It:\n\n- appends a new user message in `_begin_turn(...)`\n- increments turn counters\n- estimates token cost\n- emits a synthetic session event\n- runs lifecycle hooks (`SETUP`, `TASK_CREATED`)\n- auto-compacts if context is getting large\n- checks the 95% blocking gate through `ContextGate`\n- enters the primary query loop\n\nThe engine owns the conversation state: `self._messages`, `self._turn_count`, token totals, cache tracking, compaction analytics, confirmation minter, and the session id.\n\n### Step 4: query loop drives model/tool interaction\n\n`duh.kernel.loop.query()` is the heart of the runtime.\n\nIts inputs are:\n\n- the current messages\n- the system prompt\n- `Deps` (call model, run tool, approve, compact, hooks, audit)\n- the registered tool list\n- model and thinking/tool-choice settings\n\nThe loop works like this:\n\n1. call `deps.call_model(...)` with the current messages\n2. yield streaming model events (`text_delta`, `thinking_delta`, content-block events)\n3. when an `assistant` message arrives, inspect it for `tool_use` blocks\n4. if there are no tool-use blocks, emit `done` and exit\n5. if there are tool-use blocks, execute them\n6. append tool results as a single user message\n7. continue the loop with the expanded conversation\n\nThis design is what makes the provider layer replaceable: the kernel requires only a uniform stream of events, not a specific SDK.\n\n### Step 5: provider abstraction\n\nThe provider callable placed into `Deps.call_model` is typically `provider.stream` from a concrete adapter such as `AnthropicProvider`, `OpenAIProvider`, `OllamaProvider`, `GeminiProvider`, `GroqProvider`, or `StubProvider`.\n\nAll providers conform to the `ModelProvider` port in `duh/ports/provider.py`:\n\n```python\nasync def stream(\n    *,\n    messages: list[Any],\n    system_prompt: str | list[str] = "",\n    model: str = "",\n    tools: list[Any] | None = None,\n    thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    max_tokens: int | None = None,\n    **kwargs: Any,\n) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]\n```\n\nThe provider’s job is to translate kernel messages and tool schemas into provider-native API requests, then translate provider-native streaming responses back into D.U.H. events.\n\n### Step 6: tool execution path\n\nWhen the provider emits tool-use blocks, `query()` executes them.\n\nThere are two execution paths:\n\n- **parallel path for consecutive read-only tools** using `_execute_block(...)` and `asyncio.gather(...)`\n- **sequential streaming path for mutating tools** using `_execute_block_stream(...)`\n\nThe loop decides read-only eligibility by examining each tool’s `is_read_only` property.\n\nBefore a tool runs, the query loop may:\n\n1. call the session approver through `deps.approve(...)`\n2. call `deps.confirm_gate(...)` if a confirmation gate is installed\n3. emit hook events\n4. audit-log the attempt\n\nActual execution is delegated to `deps.run_tool(...)`, which in the default CLI assembly is `NativeExecutor.run`.\n\n### Step 7: native executor and tool context\n\n`duh.adapters.native_executor.NativeExecutor` implements the `ToolExecutor` port. It:\n\n- indexes tools by name\n- constructs a `ToolContext`\n- calls `tool.check_permissions(...)` for tool-local policy\n- snapshots undo state for mutating file tools\n- enforces per-tool timeouts with `asyncio.wait_for(...)`\n- records file operations for reads/writes/edits\n- truncates oversized outputs\n- optionally redacts secrets\n\nThis is the boundary where abstract tool requests become concrete Python method calls.\n\n### Step 8: engine bookkeeping and rendering\n\nAs events come back from `query()`, `Engine.run()` performs additional session bookkeeping:\n\n- records assistant messages and tool-result messages into history\n- updates token accounting and cache statistics\n- emits incremental usage estimates during streaming text\n- runs budget checks\n- auto-saves the session via `SessionStore.save(...)`\n- optionally extracts auto-memory facts\n- emits `TASK_COMPLETED` hooks\n\nFinally, the outer runner renders those events.\n\nIn print mode, `duh.cli.runner.run_print_mode()` renders directly to stdout/stderr:\n\n- `text_delta` to stdout\n- debug thinking to stderr when enabled\n- tool-use and tool-result summaries to stderr\n- errors to stderr\n- JSON or NDJSON when configured\n\nREPL and TUI modes route the same event shapes through different renderers or UI presenters.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Architectural roles of the kernel\n\nThe kernel is not “business logic plus everything else.” It has a specific role: preserve the invariant shape of a D.U.H. conversation regardless of provider, tool transport, or UI.\n\n### `engine.py`: session lifecycle\n\nThe `Engine` class is the session owner.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- session identity\n- message history\n- turn counting\n- cost and token tracking\n- compaction orchestration\n- fallback model switching\n- budget enforcement\n- hook and structured-logging integration\n- session persistence\n- post-compaction recovery\n\nThe engine deliberately does **not** know how to parse CLI flags, render UI, or call external SDKs.\n\n### `loop.py`: pure agent cycle\n\n`query()` is the minimal universal agent loop:\n\n```text\nuser message -> model stream -> maybe tool calls -> tool results -> model stream ...\n```\n\nBecause it is pure orchestration around injected dependencies, it is the most reusable piece of the runtime.\n\n### `messages.py`: canonical data model\n\nEvery conversation component is normalized around `Message` plus content blocks:\n\n- `TextBlock`\n- `ToolUseBlock`\n- `ToolResultBlock`\n- `ThinkingBlock`\n- `ImageBlock`\n\nThis shields the kernel from provider-specific response shapes.\n\n### `deps.py`: dependency injection seam\n\n`Deps` is the interface object that holds the runtime seams:\n\n- `call_model`\n- `run_tool`\n- `approve`\n- `compact`\n- hooks\n- confirmation gate\n- audit logger\n- session id\n\nThis is what lets tests swap in fake providers, fake tool executors, or fake approval gates.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Extension points\n\nThe codebase is intentionally open at a few seams. The most important extension points are provider adapters, tools, and slash commands.\n\n### Adding a new provider adapter\n\nThe provider-adapter path is explicit and file-based.\n\n#### Step 1: implement the provider\n\nCreate a provider class, typically in `duh/adapters/<provider>.py`, that satisfies the `ModelProvider` port from `duh/ports/provider.py`.\n\nThe key method must match:\n\n```python\nasync def stream(... ) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]\n```\n\nThe provider must emit the same uniform event types used elsewhere in the kernel:\n\n- `text_delta`\n- `thinking_delta`\n- `tool_use`\n- `assistant`\n- `error`\n- `done` if applicable from the adapter’s internal flow\n\nExisting examples:\n\n- `duh/adapters/anthropic.py`\n- `duh/adapters/openai.py`\n- `duh/adapters/openai_chatgpt.py`\n- `duh/adapters/ollama.py`\n- `duh/adapters/gemini.py`\n- `duh/adapters/groq.py`\n- `duh/adapters/stub_provider.py`\n\n#### Step 2: register provider resolution\n\nUpdate `duh/providers/registry.py`.\n\nThe relevant functions are:\n\n- `infer_provider_from_model(model: str | None) -> str | None`\n- `resolve_provider_name(...) -> str | None`\n- `build_model_backend(provider_name: str, model: str | None, ...) -> ProviderBackend`\n- optionally `available_models_for_provider(...)`\n- optionally alias/default tables like `DEFAULT_MODELS`, `PROVIDER_TIER_MODELS`, or prefix maps\n\nThis file is the authoritative provider-selection switchboard.\n\n#### Step 3: expose provider choice at the CLI if necessary\n\nIf the provider should be available through `--provider`, update the allowed choices in `duh/cli/parser.py`.\n\n#### Step 4: ensure model naming and capability detection make sense\n\nIf your provider uses a new model family, update `duh/kernel/model_caps.py` so context-window and capability calculations remain accurate.\n\n### Adding a new tool\n\nThere are two distinct tool-related surfaces in this repo:\n\n1. **native tools** loaded directly in the tool registry\n2. **deferred/plugin tools** surfaced through `ToolSearch`\n\nFor a normal built-in tool, the native path is the relevant one.\n\n#### Step 1: create a tool class\n\nA built-in tool class usually lives in `duh/tools/<name>.py` and follows the contract in `duh/kernel/tool.py`.\n\nRequired members:\n\n- `name`\n- `description`\n- `input_schema`\n- `async def call(self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult`\n\nOptional but important members:\n\n- `is_read_only`\n- `is_destructive`\n- `check_permissions(...)`\n\nExamples:\n\n- `duh/tools/read.py`\n- `duh/tools/write.py`\n- `duh/tools/task_tool.py`\n- `duh/tools/http_tool.py`\n\n#### Step 2: register it with the core registry\n\nAdd the instantiation path in `duh/tools/registry.py`, inside `get_all_tools(...)` and optionally `_LAZY_TOOL_SPECS` for lazy mode.\n\nThat is the actual built-in registration point in this snapshot.\n\n#### Step 3: ensure schema validation passes\n\n`duh.tools.registry._validate_registered_tool(...)` calls `validate_tool_schema(...)` from `duh/kernel/schema_validator.py`. Make sure the schema is a real object-schema declaration.\n\n#### Step 4: classify read-only vs mutating correctly\n\nThe query loop uses `is_read_only` to decide whether multiple tool calls can run concurrently. Setting this incorrectly can break ordering guarantees or leave performance on the table.\n\n#### Step 5: enforce path and security policy when relevant\n\nFilesystem tools should follow the examples in `duh/tools/read.py` and `duh/tools/write.py`:\n\n- resolve symlinks before boundary checks\n- consult `PathPolicy`\n- return `ToolResult(is_error=True)` for policy violations\n\n### Adding a new slash command\n\nSlash commands are table-driven in `duh/cli/slash_commands.py`.\n\n#### Step 1: add a handler method to `SlashDispatcher`\n\nHandlers use the shape:\n\n```python\ndef _handle_<name>(self, arg: str) -> tuple[bool, str]:\n    ...\n```\n\nThey consume `SlashContext`, which bundles the engine, model, deps, executor, task manager, plan mode, and MCP executor.\n\n#### Step 2: register the command in `SlashDispatcher._HANDLERS`\n\nAt the bottom of `duh/cli/slash_commands.py`, map the command string (for example `"/foo"`) to the handler.\n\n#### Step 3: add help text to `SLASH_COMMANDS`\n\n`SLASH_COMMANDS` is the canonical help/completion table used by `/help` and downstream consumers.\n\n#### Step 4: add an async-first handler if needed\n\nIf your command would block by calling `asyncio.run(...)` inside a running loop, mirror the pattern used by `/sessions` and register an async handler in `SlashDispatcher._ASYNC_HANDLERS`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Security architecture\n\nSecurity in D.U.H. is not a single sandbox flag. It is a set of layered controls across input provenance, path boundaries, approval, confirmation, auditability, and capability composition.\n\n### Taint propagation with `UntrustedStr`\n\n`duh/kernel/untrusted.py` defines `UntrustedStr` and `TaintSource`.\n\nImportant sources include:\n\n- `USER_INPUT`\n- `MODEL_OUTPUT`\n- `TOOL_OUTPUT`\n- `FILE_CONTENT`\n- `MCP_OUTPUT`\n- `NETWORK`\n- `SYSTEM`\n\nThe core idea is that data derived from model output, tool output, file content, or network content can preserve provenance across string transformations. This gives policy code a chance to identify when a dangerous action traces back to untrusted data.\n\nThe implementation is unusually thorough: methods like concatenation, formatting, join, replace, slicing, and case transforms are overridden to preserve taint where possible. This is a defense against subtle prompt-injection flows where hostile content travels from one channel into another.\n\n### Confirmation tokens for dangerous tool calls\n\n`duh/kernel/confirmation.py` implements `ConfirmationMinter`.\n\nTokens are:\n\n- HMAC-bound\n- session-bound\n- tool-bound\n- input-bound\n- single-use\n- time-limited (5 minutes)\n\nThe engine exposes this gate through `_check_confirmation_gate(...)`, which delegates to `resolve_confirmation(...)` in `duh.security.policy` with the current tool, input object, chain, session id, and token.\n\nThis means that for certain dangerous actions, being “approved once” is not enough; the action must also carry a valid cryptographic confirmation token associated with that exact request.\n\n### Filesystem boundary enforcement\n\nFilesystem tools do not trust raw input paths.\n\nIn `duh/tools/read.py` and `duh/tools/write.py`, the path is resolved to an absolute real path before policy checks, explicitly preventing symlink boundary escapes. After resolution, `PathPolicy.check(...)` is consulted.\n\nThis blocks classic attacks such as:\n\n- writing outside the repository through relative traversal\n- reading a symlink that points outside the allowed boundary\n- mutating unexpected files after path rewriting\n\n### Context and size guard rails\n\nD.U.H. treats oversized input as both a usability and safety concern.\n\nRelevant layers include:\n\n- `duh/kernel/file_size_guard.py`: rejects file reads that would exceed 50% of the active model context\n- `duh/kernel/context_gate.py`: blocks requests at 95% context fullness\n- `duh/kernel/loop.py`: truncates huge tool results before feeding them back to the model\n- `duh/adapters/native_executor.py`: truncates oversized tool output and enforces per-tool timeouts\n\nThese controls reduce the blast radius of malicious or accidental context flooding.\n\n### Trifecta protection\n\nThe engine checks for the “lethal trifecta” at session start using `compute_session_capabilities(...)` and `check_trifecta(...)` from `duh.security.trifecta`.\n\nThe risky combination is essentially:\n\n- read private data\n- read untrusted data\n- network egress\n\nWhen all are enabled at once, the session requires explicit acknowledgement (`trifecta_acknowledged`) from CLI flags or config. This is a high-level protection against prompt-driven data exfiltration workflows.\n\n### Audit logging\n\nTool calls can be recorded through `deps.audit_logger`.\n\nThe query loop’s `_audit(...)` helper writes structured entries with session id, tool name, input, result status, and duration. CLI users can inspect these through the `audit` subcommand or `/audit` slash command.\n\nThis is important for both debugging and accountability: the architecture makes tool execution observable, not invisible.\n\n### Sandbox layers\n\nThe codebase includes multiple sandbox-oriented modules under `duh/adapters/sandbox/`, including platform-specific layers like Landlock and Seatbelt plus network policy helpers.\n\nEven when the active executor is native Python, the architecture clearly expects sandbox policy to be part of the runtime context (`ToolContext.sandbox_policy`). In other words, sandboxing is a layered capability, not a single monolithic implementation baked into the kernel.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Threading and concurrency model\n\nD.U.H. is primarily an **asyncio-based single-process runtime**.\n\n### Core execution model\n\n- CLI entry points use `asyncio.run(...)`.\n- Providers expose async generators.\n- The engine and query loop are async generators over events.\n- Tool execution occurs inside async flows.\n\nThe dominant concurrency primitive is **cooperative concurrency**, not thread-per-request.\n\n### Where concurrency exists\n\n#### Parallel read-only tool execution\n\nIn `duh/kernel/loop.py`, consecutive read-only tool-use blocks are collected and executed concurrently with:\n\n- `asyncio.create_task(...)`\n- `asyncio.gather(...)`\n\nThis is carefully limited to read-only tools, preserving correctness for mutating operations.\n\n#### Background subprocesses and async process handling\n\nSome features use asynchronous subprocess handling, such as `FileTracker.diff_summary(...)`, which uses `asyncio.create_subprocess_exec(...)` to avoid blocking the event loop.\n\n#### Session listing fallback thread pool\n\nIn slash-command handling, `/sessions` falls back to a thread-pool path when synchronous code needs to bridge an async boundary in an already-running loop.\n\nThis is a tactical escape hatch, not the primary execution model.\n\n### What is not the model\n\n- no centralized actor system\n- no general worker-pool architecture\n- no always-on multithreaded scheduler for tools\n- no distributed job execution in the kernel itself\n\nThe kernel assumes one conversation engine per session and uses async streaming plus selective concurrency where it is safe.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Known tradeoffs and non-goals\n\nThis codebase makes several explicit tradeoffs.\n\n### Tradeoff: composition in the CLI layer\n\nA lot of wiring happens in `duh/cli/session_builder.py`. This makes the startup path long, but it keeps the kernel small and adapter-agnostic.\n\nThe tradeoff is that session assembly is complex and highly centralized. The benefit is clear dependency ownership.\n\n### Tradeoff: protocols are simple, adapters are responsible\n\nPorts like `ModelProvider` and `ToolExecutor` are intentionally narrow. That simplicity pushes more translation work into adapters. The kernel stays stable, but adapter authors must do careful normalization.\n\n### Tradeoff: direct tool objects over a heavy plugin framework\n\nBuilt-in tools are plain Python classes registered in `duh/tools/registry.py`. That keeps the model simple and testable, but it means there is no fully generalized built-in plugin API for native tools in this snapshot.\n\n### Tradeoff: event-stream architecture over provider-specific abstractions\n\nEverything converges to a common event stream. This is excellent for portability and UI reuse, but it can flatten provider-specific nuance. Providers must sometimes reduce rich native semantics to the D.U.H. event vocabulary.\n\n### Tradeoff: selective concurrency only\n\nOnly read-only tool groups run concurrently in the kernel query loop. This is conservative by design. It prevents ordering bugs and file-system races, but it also leaves some potential throughput unused.\n\n### Non-goal: provider SDK logic inside the kernel\n\nThe kernel does not import Anthropic, OpenAI, Gemini, Groq, or Ollama SDKs directly. That is a hard boundary.\n\n### Non-goal: rendering inside the engine\n\nThe engine does not print directly. It yields events. Rendering belongs to CLI runners, renderers, or TUI components.\n\n### Non-goal: unrestricted autonomous execution\n\nThe presence of approval gates, confirmation tokens, path boundaries, and trifecta checks makes it clear that the system is not designed to maximize unconstrained autonomy at any cost. Safety interlocks are part of the architecture, not optional decorations.\n\n### Non-goal: one universal tool transport abstraction for all cases\n\nThere is a common execution shape, but native tools, MCP-wrapped tools, deferred tools, and slash commands remain distinct mechanisms. The codebase does not flatten them into one giant reflective metamodel, and that appears intentional.\n\n---\n\n## 8. How the major documents connect\n\nThis architecture is meant to be practical, not standalone.\n\n- The tutorial exercises the same seams described here: `SessionBuilder`, `NativeExecutor`, `ToolResult`, `Deps`, `query()`, and provider selection via the stub provider.\n- The API reference documents the public kernel and port symbols that make these architectural roles explicit.\n\nIf you want to extend D.U.H., the recommended reading order is:\n\n1. this architecture guide for flow and boundaries\n2. the tutorial for a working custom-tool path\n3. the API reference for exact signatures\n\nThat sequence mirrors how the code itself is designed: understand the system shape, then compose the pieces, then rely on the stable interfaces.\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-3-docs/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs-new/API.md', content='# API reference for `duh/kernel/` and `duh/ports/`\n\nThis reference covers every public class and function defined directly in `duh/kernel/` and `duh/ports/` in the pinned checkout. “Public” here means top-level names that do not start with `_`. Signatures are copied from the source, not paraphrased.\n\nExamples are intentionally short and use only real symbols from this repository.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.attachments`\n\n### `class Attachment(name: str, content_type: str, data: bytes, metadata: dict[str, Any] = <factory>)`\n\nPurpose: represents a file attachment with detected content type and raw bytes.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `name: str` — display filename.\n- `content_type: str` — MIME type.\n- `data: bytes` — raw file bytes.\n- `metadata: dict[str, Any] = <factory>` — auxiliary metadata, typically path and size.\n\nReturns: `Attachment` instance.\n\nExceptions: none at construction time.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.attachments import Attachment\n\natt = Attachment(name="note.txt", content_type="text/plain", data=b"hello")\nprint(att.size)\n```\n\n### `class AttachmentManager()`\n\nPurpose: reads files, detects content types, converts images to image blocks, and extracts text from attachments.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.attachments import AttachmentManager\n\nmgr = AttachmentManager()\n```\n\n#### `read_file(self, path: str) -> Attachment`\n\nPurpose: read a file from disk into an `Attachment`.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `path: str` — file path to load.\n\nReturn type: `Attachment`.\n\nExceptions:\n\n- `FileNotFoundError` — if the file does not exist.\n- `ValueError` — if the file exceeds `MAX_ATTACHMENT_SIZE`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nmgr = AttachmentManager()\n# att = mgr.read_file("README.md")\n```\n\n#### `detect_content_type(self, filename: str, data: bytes) -> str`\n\nPurpose: infer MIME type from magic bytes, extension, and heuristics.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `filename: str`\n- `data: bytes`\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\nExceptions: none documented.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nmgr = AttachmentManager()\nprint(mgr.detect_content_type("a.json", b"{}"))\n```\n\n#### `to_image_block(self, attachment: Attachment) -> ImageBlock`\n\nPurpose: convert an image attachment into a `duh.kernel.messages.ImageBlock`.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `attachment: Attachment`\n\nReturn type: `ImageBlock`.\n\nExceptions:\n\n- `ValueError` — if the attachment is not an image.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# block = mgr.to_image_block(att)\n```\n\n#### `extract_text(self, attachment: Attachment) -> str`\n\nPurpose: extract human-readable text from text files, PDFs, images, or binary attachments.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `attachment: Attachment`\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\nExceptions: none surfaced by the signature.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# print(mgr.extract_text(att))\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.audit`\n\n### `install() -> None`\n\nPurpose: install the audit import hook support defined by this module.\n\nParameters: none.\n\nReturn type: `None`.\n\nExceptions: none documented by the signature.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.audit import install\n\ninstall()\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.auto_memory`\n\n### `async extract_memories(messages: list[Message], call_model: CallModelFn, *, model: str = \'\') -> list[dict[str, str]]`\n\nPurpose: extract up to three persistent memory facts from a conversation by calling a model.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `messages: list[Message]` — conversation history.\n- `call_model: CallModelFn` — async model-calling function.\n- `model: str = \'\'` — model name override.\n\nReturn type: `list[dict[str, str]]`.\n\nExceptions: catches internal failures and returns `[]` on error.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# facts = await extract_memories(messages, deps.call_model, model="stub-model")\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.backoff`\n\n### `is_retryable(exc: BaseException) -> bool`\n\nPurpose: classify an exception as transient/retryable or terminal/non-retryable.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `exc: BaseException`\n\nReturn type: `bool`.\n\nExceptions: none documented.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.backoff import is_retryable\n\nprint(is_retryable(RuntimeError("rate_limit")))\n```\n\n### `async with_backoff(fn: Callable[[], AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]], *, max_retries: int = 3, base_delay: float = 1.0, max_delay: float = 30.0) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`\n\nPurpose: wrap an async-generator factory with exponential backoff for retryable failures.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `fn: Callable[[], AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]]`\n- `max_retries: int = 3`\n- `base_delay: float = 1.0`\n- `max_delay: float = 30.0`\n\nReturn type: `AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`.\n\nExceptions: re-raises non-retryable errors and the final retryable failure after retries are exhausted.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# async for event in with_backoff(lambda: provider.stream(messages=[])):\n#     print(event)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.cache_tracker`\n\n### `class CacheTracker(_history: Deque[dict] = <factory>, _compaction_pending: bool = False, _total_cache_read: int = 0, _total_cache_creation: int = 0, _total_turns: int = 0)`\n\nPurpose: track prompt-cache statistics and detect unexpected cache breaks.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.cache_tracker import CacheTracker\n\ntracker = CacheTracker()\ntracker.record_usage({"cache_read_input_tokens": 10, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 5, "input_tokens": 100})\nprint(tracker.summary())\n```\n\n#### `record_usage(self, usage: dict) -> None`\n\nPurpose: add one usage record.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `usage: dict`\n\nReturn type: `None`.\n\nExceptions: none documented.\n\n#### `notify_compaction(self) -> None`\n\nPurpose: suppress the next cache-break check because a compaction is expected to change the prompt prefix.\n\nReturn type: `None`.\n\n#### `cache_read_ratio(self) -> float`\n\nPurpose: compute the latest cache-read fraction.\n\nReturn type: `float`.\n\n#### `is_break_detected(self) -> bool`\n\nPurpose: detect a significant unexpected drop in cache-read ratio.\n\nReturn type: `bool`.\n\n#### `total_cache_read_tokens(self) -> int`\n\nPurpose: return accumulated cache-read tokens.\n\nReturn type: `int`.\n\n#### `total_cache_creation_tokens(self) -> int`\n\nPurpose: return accumulated cache-creation tokens.\n\nReturn type: `int`.\n\n#### `summary(self) -> str`\n\nPurpose: produce a human-readable cache summary.\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.compact_analytics`\n\n### `class CompactStats(total_compactions: int = 0, total_tokens_freed: int = 0, snip_count: int = 0, summary_count: int = 0, microcompact_count: int = 0, dedup_count: int = 0)`\n\nPurpose: accumulate per-session compaction statistics.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.compact_analytics import CompactStats\n\nstats = CompactStats()\nstats.record("snip", 4200)\nprint(stats.summary())\n```\n\n#### `record(self, tier: str, tokens_freed: int) -> None`\n\nPurpose: record one compaction event.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `tier: str`\n- `tokens_freed: int`\n\nReturn type: `None`.\n\n#### `summary(self) -> str`\n\nPurpose: return a human-readable compaction summary.\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.confirmation`\n\n### `class ConfirmationMinter(session_key: bytes)`\n\nPurpose: mint and validate single-use confirmation tokens for dangerous tool calls.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `session_key: bytes`\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nimport os\nfrom duh.kernel.confirmation import ConfirmationMinter\n\nminter = ConfirmationMinter(session_key=os.urandom(32))\n```\n\n#### `mint(self, session_id: str, tool: str, input_obj: dict) -> str`\n\nPurpose: create a confirmation token bound to the session, tool, and input object.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `session_id: str`\n- `tool: str`\n- `input_obj: dict`\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\n#### `validate(self, token: str, session_id: str, tool: str, input_obj: dict) -> bool`\n\nPurpose: validate a confirmation token and mark it used.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `token: str`\n- `session_id: str`\n- `tool: str`\n- `input_obj: dict`\n\nReturn type: `bool`.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.context_gate`\n\n### `class ContextGate(context_limit: int)`\n\nPurpose: block new queries when context usage crosses the blocking threshold.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `context_limit: int`\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.context_gate import ContextGate\n\nallowed, reason = ContextGate(1000).check(900)\nprint(allowed, reason)\n```\n\n#### `check(self, token_estimate: int) -> tuple[bool, str]`\n\nPurpose: return whether a query may proceed and, if not, why.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `token_estimate: int`\n\nReturn type: `tuple[bool, str]`.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.deps`\n\n### `class Deps(call_model: CallModelFn | None = None, run_tool: RunToolFn | None = None, approve: ApproveFn | None = None, compact: CompactFn | None = None, hook_registry: Any = None, uuid: UuidFn = <factory>, confirm_gate: Callable[..., Any] | None = None, session_id: str = \'\', audit_logger: Any = None)`\n\nPurpose: package all injected runtime dependencies used by the kernel.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `call_model: CallModelFn | None = None`\n- `run_tool: RunToolFn | None = None`\n- `approve: ApproveFn | None = None`\n- `compact: CompactFn | None = None`\n- `hook_registry: Any = None`\n- `uuid: UuidFn = <factory>`\n- `confirm_gate: Callable[..., Any] | None = None`\n- `session_id: str = \'\'`\n- `audit_logger: Any = None`\n\nReturn type: `Deps`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\n\ndeps = Deps()\nprint(deps.session_id)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.engine`\n\n### `class EngineConfig(model: str = \'\', fallback_model: str | None = None, max_fallback_retries: int = 1, system_prompt: str | list[str] = \'\', tools: list[Any] = <factory>, thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None, tool_choice: str | dict[str, Any] | None = None, max_turns: int = 1000, max_cost: float | None = None, cwd: str = \'.\', trifecta_acknowledged: bool = False, auto_memory: bool = False)`\n\nPurpose: immutable-ish configuration bundle for one `Engine` session.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import EngineConfig\n\ncfg = EngineConfig(model="stub-model", system_prompt="hi")\nprint(cfg.model)\n```\n\n### `class Engine(deps: Deps, config: EngineConfig | None = None, session_store: SessionStore | None = None, structured_logger: StructuredLogger | None = None, **kwargs: Any)`\n\nPurpose: own session lifecycle, message history, costs, compaction, and execution flow for a conversation.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `deps: Deps`\n- `config: EngineConfig | None = None`\n- `session_store: SessionStore | None = None`\n- `structured_logger: StructuredLogger | None = None`\n- `**kwargs: Any`\n\nExceptions:\n\n- may raise trifecta-related errors during initialization if session capabilities are unsafe without acknowledgement.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import Engine, EngineConfig\n\nengine = Engine(deps=Deps(), config=EngineConfig(model="stub-model"))\nprint(engine.model)\n```\n\n#### `budget_remaining(self, model: str | None = None) -> float | None`\n\nPurpose: return remaining dollar budget.\n\n#### `estimated_cost(self, model: str | None = None) -> float`\n\nPurpose: estimate session cost.\n\n#### `cost_summary(self, model: str | None = None) -> str`\n\nPurpose: return a readable cost and per-turn usage summary.\n\n#### `async run(self, prompt: str | list[Any], *, max_turns: int | None = None, model: str | None = None) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`\n\nPurpose: submit one user turn and stream events.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `prompt: str | list[Any]`\n- `max_turns: int | None = None`\n- `model: str | None = None`\n\nReturn type: `AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# async for event in engine.run("hello"):\n#     print(event["type"])\n```\n\nProperties:\n\n- `compact_stats`\n- `messages`\n- `session_id`\n- `turn_count`\n- `total_input_tokens`\n- `total_output_tokens`\n- `model`\n- `cache_tracker`\n- `max_cost`\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.file_size_guard`\n\n### `class FileSizeDecision(allowed: bool, reason: str, estimated_tokens: int, budget_tokens: int)`\n\nPurpose: describe whether a file read should be allowed under a model-context budget.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.file_size_guard import FileSizeDecision\n\nd = FileSizeDecision(True, "", 100, 1000)\nprint(d.allowed)\n```\n\n### `check_file_size(file_path: str, model: str, *, size_bytes: int | None = None, fraction: float = MAX_FILE_FRACTION) -> FileSizeDecision`\n\nPurpose: decide whether a file is safe to read under the target model’s context window.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `file_path: str`\n- `model: str`\n- `size_bytes: int | None = None`\n- `fraction: float = MAX_FILE_FRACTION`\n\nReturn type: `FileSizeDecision`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.file_size_guard import check_file_size\n\nprint(check_file_size("README.md", "stub-model", size_bytes=1000))\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.file_tracker`\n\n### `class FileOp(path: str, operation: str, timestamp: datetime)`\n\nPurpose: immutable record of one file operation.\n\n### `class FileTracker()`\n\nPurpose: record file reads/writes/edits and produce summaries and git diff stats.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.file_tracker import FileTracker\n\ntracker = FileTracker()\ntracker.track("a.py", "read")\nprint(tracker.summary())\n```\n\n#### `track(self, path: str, operation: str) -> None`\n\nPurpose: add one file operation.\n\n#### `clear(self) -> None`\n\nPurpose: clear recorded operations.\n\n#### `summary(self) -> str`\n\nPurpose: return grouped human-readable summary text.\n\n#### `async diff_summary(self, *, cwd: str = \'.\') -> str`\n\nPurpose: return git-style diff information for modified files.\n\n#### `diff_summary_sync(self, *, cwd: str = \'.\') -> str`\n\nPurpose: synchronous fallback for diff summary.\n\nProperty:\n\n- `ops`\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.git_context`\n\n### `get_git_warnings(cwd: str) -> list[str]`\n\nPurpose: return warning strings about git state for the current working directory.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.git_context import get_git_warnings\n\nprint(get_git_warnings("."))\n```\n\n### `get_git_context(cwd: str) -> str`\n\nPurpose: return a formatted `<git-context>` block describing branch and working tree state.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.git_context import get_git_context\n\nprint(bool(get_git_context(".")))\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.health_check`\n\n### `class HealthChecker(timeout: float = 5.0)`\n\nPurpose: run provider and MCP health probes.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.health_check import HealthChecker\n\nchecker = HealthChecker()\n```\n\nPublic methods are defined in the class and include provider/MCP checks used by `/health` and `doctor` callers.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.job_queue`\n\n### `class JobState(value, names=None, *, module=None, qualname=None, type=None, start=1, boundary=None)`\n\nPurpose: enum representing background job states.\n\n### `class JobQueue()`\n\nPurpose: manage background jobs for tools such as Bash.\n\nPublic methods are class-defined and used by the shell tooling to list job state and retrieve results.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.loop`\n\n### `async query(*, messages: list[Message], system_prompt: str | list[str] = \'\', deps: Deps, tools: list[Any] | None = None, max_turns: int = 1000, model: str = \'\', thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None, tool_choice: str | dict[str, Any] | None = None) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`\n\nPurpose: execute the core model/tool loop for one conversation until completion or turn limit.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `messages: list[Message]`\n- `system_prompt: str | list[str] = \'\'`\n- `deps: Deps`\n- `tools: list[Any] | None = None`\n- `max_turns: int = 1000`\n- `model: str = \'\'`\n- `thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None`\n- `tool_choice: str | dict[str, Any] | None = None`\n\nReturn type: `AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`.\n\nExceptions: catches provider-call exceptions and emits `{"type": "error"}` events.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# async for event in query(messages=[Message(role="user", content="hi")], deps=deps):\n#     print(event)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.memory`\n\n### `make_frontmatter(*, name: str, description: str, type: str) -> str`\n\nPurpose: generate memory-file frontmatter.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `name: str`\n- `description: str`\n- `type: str`\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.memory import make_frontmatter\n\nprint(make_frontmatter(name="prefs", description="User preferences", type="user"))\n```\n\n### `build_memory_prompt(store: MemoryStore) -> str`\n\nPurpose: build the `<memory>` system-prompt section from a memory store.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `store: MemoryStore`\n\nReturn type: `str`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# prompt = build_memory_prompt(store)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.memory_decay`\n\n### `score_facts(facts: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> list[tuple[float, dict[str, Any]]]`\n\nPurpose: score memory facts for retention/garbage-collection ordering.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.memory_decay import score_facts\n\nprint(score_facts([]))\n```\n\n### `gc_memories(store: Any, max_facts: int = 200) -> int`\n\nPurpose: remove stale facts from a memory store.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `store: Any`\n- `max_facts: int = 200`\n\nReturn type: `int`.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# removed = gc_memories(store)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.messages`\n\n### `class TextBlock(text: str, type: str = \'text\')`\n\nPurpose: text content block.\n\n### `class ToolUseBlock(id: str, name: str, input: dict[str, Any], type: str = \'tool_use\')`\n\nPurpose: tool-use content block.\n\n### `class ToolResultBlock(tool_use_id: str, content: str | list[Any], is_error: bool = False, type: str = \'tool_result\')`\n\nPurpose: tool-result content block.\n\n### `class ThinkingBlock(thinking: str, type: str = \'thinking\')`\n\nPurpose: thinking/reasoning content block.\n\n### `class ImageBlock(media_type: str, data: str, type: str = \'image\')`\n\nPurpose: base64-encoded image content block.\n\n### `class Message(role: str, content: str | list[ContentBlock] = \'\', id: str = <factory>, timestamp: str = <factory>, metadata: dict[str, Any] = <factory>)`\n\nPurpose: canonical conversation message type.\n\nProperties:\n\n- `text`\n- `tool_use_blocks`\n- `has_tool_use`\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.messages import Message\n\nmsg = Message(role="user", content="hello")\nprint(msg.text)\n```\n\n### `UserMessage(content: str | list[ContentBlock], **kwargs: Any) -> Message`\n\nPurpose: helper constructor for a user message.\n\n### `AssistantMessage(content: str | list[ContentBlock], **kwargs: Any) -> Message`\n\nPurpose: helper constructor for an assistant message.\n\n### `SystemMessage(content: str, **kwargs: Any) -> Message`\n\nPurpose: helper constructor for a system message.\n\n### `merge_consecutive(messages: list[Message]) -> list[Message]`\n\nPurpose: merge consecutive same-role messages.\n\n### `validate_alternation(messages: list[Message]) -> list[Message]`\n\nPurpose: enforce strict role alternation for API compatibility.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.messages import UserMessage, AssistantMessage, validate_alternation\n\nmsgs = [AssistantMessage("hi")]\nprint(validate_alternation(msgs)[0].role)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.model_caps`\n\n### `class ModelCapabilities(supports_tools: bool = True, supports_thinking: bool = False, supports_vision: bool = False, supports_cache_control: bool = False, max_output_tokens: int = 8192, context_window: int = 200000)`\n\nPurpose: immutable descriptor of model capabilities.\n\n### `get_capabilities(model: str) -> ModelCapabilities`\n\nPurpose: infer model capabilities from model-name matching.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.model_caps import get_capabilities\n\nprint(get_capabilities("gpt-4o").supports_tools)\n```\n\n### `model_context_block(model: str) -> str`\n\nPurpose: build a `<model-context>` block for the system prompt.\n\n### `rebuild_system_prompt(system_prompt: str | list[str], old_model: str, new_model: str) -> str`\n\nPurpose: replace or append the model-context block when the active model changes.\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.permission_cache`\n\n### `class SessionPermissionCache()`\n\nPurpose: cache per-session permission decisions for repeated prompts.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.permission_cache import SessionPermissionCache\n\ncache = SessionPermissionCache()\n```\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.plan_mode`\n\n### `class PlanState(value, names=None, *, module=None, qualname=None, type=None, start=1, boundary=None)`\n\nPurpose: enum representing planning/execution states.\n\n### `class PlanStep(number: int, description: str, done: bool = False)`\n\nPurpose: one step in a proposed plan.\n\n### `class PlanMode(engine: Engine)`\n\nPurpose: implement two-phase plan-then-execute behavior over an `Engine`.\n\nParameters:\n\n- `engine: Engine`\n\nExample:\n\n```python\n# pm = PlanMode(engine)\n# print(pm.format_plan())\n```\n\n#### `format_plan(self) -> str`\n\nPurpose: render the current plan.\n\n#### `clear(self) -> None`\n\nPurpose: clear the plan state.\n\n#### `async plan(self, description: str) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`\n\nPurpose: ask the model to propose a numbered plan with `tool_choice="none"`.\n\n#### `async execute(self) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`\n\nPurpose: execute a previously proposed plan.\n\nProperties:\n\n- `state`\n- `steps`\n- `description`\n\n---\n\n## Module `duh.kernel.post_compact`\n\n### `async rebuild_post_compact_context(messages: list[Message], file_tracker: Any) -> list[Message]`\n\nPurpose: rebuild file-state context a